<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - CYLINDER HEAD AND VALVES - CYLINDER HEAD RECONDITIONING -
        VALVE AND VALVE GUIDE RECONDITIONING
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="21">
        <title>VALVE AND VALVE GUIDE RECONDITIONING</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Remove Valves</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a valve spring compressor tool (
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE1846</emph>), remove the valves as follows:
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the valve spring compressor over the valve to be removed and compress the
                    spring.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the valve spring locks (keepers). Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050427">4.27</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the valve spring compressor tool.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the valve rotator, valve spring, valve seal and valve as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050428">4.28</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                    <emph type="bold"></emph>If the nylon rotator seal becomes dislodged from the rotator and sticks to
                    the valve stem, remove the seal from the valve stem with your fingers. Discard all 12 rotator seals.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Separate the intake and exhaust springs at time of removal. The spring rates are different
                            and cannot be mixed on cylinder head reassembly.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove valve stem seal assemblies and valves. Discard all 12 stem seal assemblies due to
                    damage from removal across the valve keeper grooves.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1050427" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg1720" filename="../figeg1/eg1720.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.27.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050428" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2311" filename="../figeg2/eg2311.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.28.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Cylinder Head</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Valve Rotator with Nylon Seal</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Spring</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. Valve Stem Seal</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Clean Valve Guides</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With valves removed, clean all valve guides using a nylon brush
                    <emph type="bold">(OEM6343)</emph>, soap and water. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050429">4.29</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1050429" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg1706" filename="../figeg1/eg1706.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.29.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Brush</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Valve Guide</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Inspect Valve Guides</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position an inspection light at the bottom of the valve guide bores and visually examine
                    the walls for burning, cracking. Replace any guides which do not pass the visual inspection.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure each valve guide using a ball gauge and outside micrometer as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figures
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050430">4.30</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    and
                    <emph type="bold">
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050431">4.31</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>MEASURE THE VALVE GUIDES WITHIN 0.025 INCH (0.64 MM) OF EACH END OF THE GUIDE AND 90
                            DEGREES FROM THE CRANKSHAFT CENTER-LINE. RECORD VALVE GUIDE I.D. READINGS SO VALVE-TO-GUIDE
                            RUNNING CLEARANCE MAY BE DETERMINED LATER (FIGURE
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050431">4.31</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">~ If valve guide exceeds specifications, replace the guide.</para>
                <figure id="ef1050430" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg1707" filename="../figeg1/eg1707.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.30.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Ball Gauge</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Valve Guide</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050431" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg1708" filename="../figeg1/eg1708.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.31.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Micrometer</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Ball Gauge</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Replace Valve Guides</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove any valve guides which do not pass the inspection criteria as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Insert the valve guide remover
                        <emph type="bold">ZTSE4377</emph>
                        into the guide from the valve port side of the cylinder head.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Press/drive out the valve guide with a hammer. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050432">4.32</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new valve guide inserts as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Adjust the valve guide installer tool,
                        <emph type="bold">ZTSE1943</emph>, using a caliper as shown in
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050433">4.33</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                        <emph type="bold"></emph>
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>TOOL INSERT MUST BE REVERSED SO THAT FLAT SIDE CONTACTS GUIDE. REFER TO SPECIFICATIONS
                                FOR CORRECT VALVE GUIDE HEIGHT (ABOVE TOP DECK OF THE CYLINDER HEAD) BEFORE INSTALLING
                                VALVE GUIDE. ADJUST THE TOOL TO CORRESPOND TO THE DESIRED VALVE GUIDE HEIGHT.
                            </para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="ef1050432" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg3026" filename="../figeg3/eg3026.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.32.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Valve Guide Remover Tool</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Valve Guide</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Cylinder Head</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050433" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg3027" filename="../figeg3/eg3027.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.33.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Caliper/Dial Indicator</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Valve Guide Installer Tool</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Lock Nut</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. Cylinder Head</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>INSTALL THE VALVE GUIDE INSERTS WITH THE LARGE 15 DEGREE CHAMFER END DOWN.</para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lubricate valve guide insert using clean engine oil and press into the cylinder head
                        until installer tool bottoms against cylinder head. Chilling guide may facilitate installation.
                        Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050434">4.34</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                        <emph type="bold">DO NOT</emph>
                        hammer or pound valve guide insert into cylinder head.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Deburr the valve guide, after installation, using (
                        <emph type="bold">ZTSE4393</emph>). Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure 4.36.</emph>
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>DO NOT ream valve guide I.D. after installation. Service guides are provided in a
                                finish reamed condition. Clean valve guides as described in Figure
                                <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050429">4.29</hotlnk>.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Clean Valves</title>
            <para>Remove all carbon from the valve stems and valve heads.</para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Inspect Valves</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect each valve, replacing any that show evidence of burn marks, warpage,
                    scuffing or bending.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure each valve stem for wear using a micrometer to measure valve stem diameter.
                    Record the readings.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Measure valves at three locations 90&#176; apart. Refer to the "SPECIFICATIONS" and
                            replace valves which exceed the minimum stem diameter specification.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the valve stem diameter and valve guide inside diameter measurements, recorded
                    earlier (see
                    <emph type="bold">"INSPECT VALVE GUIDES</emph>" in this section), determine valve stem-to-guide
                    running clearance. Refer to "
                    <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS"</emph>. Replace the valve or valve guide as required.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1050434" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3028" filename="../figeg3/eg3028.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.34.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Press</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Installer Tool</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Insert</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. Cylinder Head</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Reface Valves</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If valves are in serviceable condition, reface the valve to the specified angle, as required.
                        Refer to Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050435">4.35</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reface the valves as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Dress the cutting stone, prior to refacing the valves, using the dressing stud
                        attachment on the grinder.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the valve in the grinder and set to the specified angle.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Grind the valve face. Remove only the minimum amount of material necessary to true
                        up the valve face. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050436">4.36</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure valve face margin at four locations using a caliper. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050437">4.37</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The minimum valve face margin (See "SPECIFICATIONS") must be maintained across the entire
                            valve face. An insufficient margin will NOT provide proper heat dissipation and lead to
                            valve warpage or breakage. Intake and exhaust valve margins are different. Replace the valve
                            if the margin is less than the specified minimum, after grinding.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef1050435" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11326" filename="../figcg1/cg11326.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.35.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050436" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3570" filename="../figeg3/eg3570.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.36.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050437" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11068" filename="../figcg1/cg11068.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.37.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reface the valve stem tip as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Dress the cutting stone using the dressing stud on the grinder.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the valve in the grinder as shown in
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050438">4.38</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>WHEN RESURFACING THE VALVE STEM TIP, LEAVE SUFFICIENT MATERIAL SO THE VALVE LEVER
                                (ROCKER ARM) DOES NOT CONTACT THE VALVE SPRING LOCKS OR ROTATORS, DURING OPERATION.
                            </para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Touch the valve stem tip to the cutting stone removing only a minimum of material.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Refacing the valve stem tip provides a new wear surface for the rocker arm.</para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After refacing valves, insert valves in clean valve guide and check valve face contact
                    with valve seat using Prussian Blue&#8482; (or equivalent) as follows:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Spread thin film of Prussian Blue&#8482; on valve face. Insert valve into its guide.
                        Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050439">4.39</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>IF SEATS ARE ACCEPTABLE, INSTALL THE VALVES WITHOUT GRINDING THE SEATS. IF VOIDS
                                APPEAR IN THE BLUING, SEAT GRINDING IS REQUIRED.
                            </para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Apply pressure on exact center of valve head while making a quarter turn in the
                        seat. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050440">4.40</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove valve, inspect impression made on seat and on valve face.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Bluing should appear around entire contact surface of valve face and valve seat to
                        be acceptable.
                        <emph type="bold">CHECK SEVERAL TIMES TO PREVENT ERROR</emph>. If acceptable, proceed with valve
                        installation.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050438" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg12046" filename="../figcg1/cg12046.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.38.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050439" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11382" filename="../figcg1/cg11382.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.39.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050440" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg1710" filename="../figeg1/eg1710.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.40.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Valve Seat Grinding</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If required, resurface the valve seat as follows: (Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050441">4.41</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lightly lubricate and install the correct size pilot into the valve guide.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Choose the correct angle grinding stone and dress the stone. Refer to "
                        <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS</emph>" for valve seat angles.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the grinding stone over the pilot.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lower grinder head over pilot shank until wheel barely clears the valve seat. Turn
                        on power.
                        <emph type="bold">GENTLY</emph>
                        apply grinding wheel to valve seat with little pressure other than weight of the wheel.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Raise wheel frequently to prevent overheating.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Grind seat to a smooth even finish.</para>
                    <figure id="ef1050441" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11635" filename="../figcg1/cg11635.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.41.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After resurfacing, check valve seat width using a caliper as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050442">4.42</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">"SPECIFICATIONS"</emph>for seat width limits. If seat widths are excessive, they
                    may be corrected by grinding with a 15 degree smaller angle stone.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check valve recession using a straightedge and feeler gauge or a surface gauge. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figures</emph>
                    <emph type="bold">
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050443">4.43</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    and
                    <emph type="bold">
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050444">4.44</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Refer to "
                    <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS"</emph>
                    for recession limits. If valve recession is excessive, install a new valve or replace the valve
                    seat. If the valve protrudes above the deck, regrind the valve seat.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Clean valve guides as described in Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050430">4.30</hotlnk>.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>IF A NEW VALVE WILL NOT CORRECT AN EXCESSIVE RECESSION CONDITION, THE VALVE SEAT MUST BE
                            REPLACED AND REGROUND. IF THE VALVE FACE PROTRUDES ABOVE THE DECK, THE VALVE SEAT WILL HAVE
                            TO BE REGROUND DEEPER INTO THE HEAD. AFTER REGRINDING ANY SEAT, RECHECK THE SEAT WIDTH (SEE
                            FIGURE
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050437">4.37</hotlnk>) AND CONFIRM VALVE SEAT CONTACT USING PRUSSIAN BLUE&#8482;
                            (SEE FIGURES
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050439">4.39</hotlnk>
                            AND
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050440">4.40</hotlnk>.)
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef1050442" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11381" filename="../figcg1/cg11381.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.42.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050443" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3024" filename="../figeg3/eg3024.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.43.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Straightedge</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Feeler Gauge</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Valve</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050444" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3025" filename="../figeg3/eg3025.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.44.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Dial Indicator</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Cylinder Head</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Valve</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After resurfacing the valve seat, check the seat for runout, using an appropriate dial
                    indicator. Valve seat runout should not exceed limits shown in "
                    <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS"</emph>.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>IF VALVE SEAT RUNOUT, CONCENTRICITY AND/OR SEAT WIDTH CANNOT BE MAINTAINED, REPLACE AND
                            RESURFACE THE VALVE SEATS.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Valve Seat Replacement</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">USE A VALVE SEAT PULLER</emph>
                    to remove defective valve seat inserts as follows:
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>These instructions are general in nature. Follow the instructions that apply to the
                            tool.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Cut a groove in insert using stone.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Choose the appropriate size pin collet and position the collet at the valve seat
                        insert (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050445">4.45</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Expand the pin collet by turning the small handle at the top of the bridge assembly.
                        Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050446">4.46</hotlnk>.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050445" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg1683" filename="../figeg1/eg1683.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.45.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050446" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg1682" filename="../figeg1/eg1682.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.46.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Turn the large handle on the bridge assembly to pull the valve seat insert from the
                        cylinder head. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050447">4.47</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Unlock the pin collet by turning the small handle and discard the valve seat
                        insert.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Select the appropriate size valve seat insert. Refer to "
                    <emph type="bold">VALVE SEAT INSERT CHART</emph>".
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1050447" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg1673" filename="../figeg1/eg1673.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.47.</caption>
                </figure>
                <table id="et1050407">
                    <tgroup cols="3">
                        <colspec colname="1" colwidth="144p"/>
                        <colspec colname="2" colwidth="144p"/>
                        <colspec colname="3" colwidth="144p"/>
                        <spanspec namest="1" nameend="3" spanname="S1T3"/>
                        <spanspec namest="2" nameend="3" spanname="S2T3"/>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="3" spanname="S1T3">
                                    <para>valve seat insert chart</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>OVERSIZE</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colspan="2" spanname="S2T3">
                                    <para>DIAMETER OF CYLINDER HEAD COUNTERBORE</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>INSERT</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>INTAKE</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="3">
                                    <para>EXHAUST</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>STANDARD*</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>1.996-1.997 in. (50.6-50.7 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="3">
                                    <para>1.624-1.625 in. (41.2 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>0.002 in (0.05 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>1.998-1.999 in. (50.7 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="3">
                                    <para>1.626-1.627 in. (41.3 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>0.015 in. (0.381 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>2.011-2.012 in. (51-51.1 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="3">
                                    <para>1.639-1.640 in. (41.6 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="3" spanname="S1T3">
                                    <para>* Standard and 0.002 in. (0.05 mm) oversize service insert does require insert
                                        counterbore enlargement before installing.
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>STANDARD SERVICE VALVE SEAT INSERTS ARE PROVIDED IN THE CYLINDER HEAD OVERHAUL PACKAGE. IF
                            THE SEAT IS DAMAGED BEYOND THE STANDARD OR .002 IN. (0.05mm) DIAMETER, IT WILL BE NECESSARY
                            TO MACHINE THE INSERT COUNTERBORE IN THE CYLINDER HEAD FOR AN OVERSIZE SEAT INSERT. STANDARD
                            SIZE INSERTS DOES REQUIRE COUNTERBORE ENLARGEMENT.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the valve seat insert as follows:</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Chill the valve seat insert in a freezer for 30 minutes before installing.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Chilling the valve seat insert prevents peeling of metal from the cylinder head
                            counterbore during installation.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Align the insert to avoid cocking.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Press the insert into its counterbore using
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE4164A</emph>
                    for the intake and exhaust valve seat inserts. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk document="e105_70.xml" xrefid="ef1050448">4.48</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Grind the new valve seat(s) to the specified angles and width. Refer to "
                    <emph type="bold">VALVE SEAT GRINDING"</emph>
                    in this section.
                </para>
            </step1>
